## Propagating Trace Context Across RabbitMQ

The core problem: RabbitMQ doesn't automatically propagate W3C `traceparent`/`tracestate` headers. You must **inject** context into message headers on publish and **extract** it on consume.

### Publisher (Service A)

```csharp
using System.Diagnostics;

// Define an ActivitySource for your service
static readonly ActivitySource Source = new("ServiceA.Messaging");

// When publishing:
using var activity = Source.StartActivity("OrderCreated publish", ActivityKind.Producer);

var props = channel.CreateBasicProperties();
props.Headers ??= new Dictionary<string, object>();

// Inject current trace context into message headers
if (activity?.Context is ActivityContext ctx)
{
    props.Headers["traceparent"] = $"00-{ctx.TraceId}-{ctx.SpanId}-{(ctx.TraceFlags.HasFlag(ActivityTraceFlags.Recorded) ? "01" : "00")}";
    if (!string.IsNullOrEmpty(activity.TraceStateString))
        props.Headers["tracestate"] = activity.TraceStateString;
}

channel.BasicPublish(exchange, routingKey, props, body);
```

### Consumer (Service B)

```csharp
static readonly ActivitySource Source = new("ServiceB.Messaging");

// In your consumer callback:
ActivityContext parentContext = default;

if (ea.BasicProperties.Headers?.TryGetValue("traceparent", out var raw) == true)
{
    var traceparent = Encoding.UTF8.GetString((byte[])raw);
    ActivityContext.TryParse(traceparent, traceState: null, out parentContext);

    if (ea.BasicProperties.Headers.TryGetValue("tracestate", out var tsRaw))
    {
        var tracestate = Encoding.UTF8.GetString((byte[])tsRaw);
        ActivityContext.TryParse(traceparent, tracestate, out parentContext);
    }
}

// Start a new activity linked to the producer's trace
using var activity = Source.StartActivity(
    "OrderCreated process",
    ActivityKind.Consumer,
    parentContext);  // ← this is the key — sets the parent

// Now process the message; this span shares the same TraceId
```

### Wire it up in `Program.cs` (both services)

```csharp
builder.Services.AddOpenTelemetry()
    .WithTracing(t => t
        .AddSource("ServiceA.Messaging")   // or ServiceB.Messaging
        .AddAspNetCoreInstrumentation()
        .AddOtlpExporter());               // or Jaeger, Zipkin, etc.
```

### Why this works

| Step | What happens |
|---|---|
| **Publish** | `StartActivity` with `ActivityKind.Producer` creates a span. You serialize its `TraceId` + `SpanId` as `traceparent` into the AMQP header. |
| **Consume** | You parse `traceparent` back into an `ActivityContext` and pass it as the **parent** to `StartActivity`. The new span inherits the same `TraceId`. |
| **Exporter** | Both spans share a `TraceId`, so your backend (Jaeger, OTLP collector, etc.) stitches them into one distributed trace. |

### If you use MassTransit or NServiceBus

Both libraries do this automatically — they inject/extract `traceparent` for you. If you're using raw `RabbitMQ.Client`, the manual approach above is required.
